## Finding

Title: First Ask If a Path Agrees With Itself
Type: contradiction
Agent: claude

Original Claim:
Translation-strain comparison has a numerator and no denominator. Before you can say that two traditions converge or clash on a claim unit, you must measure how much that same unit varies inside each tradition, across its sub-schools, stages of practice, and polemical eras. If the internal spread is as wide as the gap you found between the two traditions, then your convergence-or-divergence verdict is mostly an artifact of which internal version you happened to pick, not a cross-tradition signal. So Lumenary should now hold that a strain score is only admissible once between-tradition strain has been shown to exceed within-tradition variance for the same unit; otherwise the comparison should be labeled selection-dependent and given no evidential weight.

Why It Might Be New:
Existing strain work measures the deformation between two traditions, and the provenance gate asks whether an apparent similarity came from historical contact. This adds a different and orthogonal control: whether the unit is even stable enough within one tradition to be compared. A comparison can pass the provenance gate (genuinely independent) and still fail this variance gate (the chosen claim unit is internally contested enough that another legitimate reading would flip the verdict). The move imports effect-size reasoning into spiritual comparison: comparative religion already notes intra-traditional diversity, but does not require a measured within-tradition spread as the denominator that every between-tradition strain score must clear.

Critique:
The statistical analogy is loose: claim units are not random samples from a distribution, so within-tradition variance is metaphorical, and there is no clean way to compute it. Worse, weighting every textual variant equally inflates the denominator. Pudgalavada was eventually marginalized, and a minority or scholastic position may not deserve the same weight as the operative mainstream that practitioners actually train. Some traditions do settle a dominant working position at a given stage despite live scholarly disputes, so treating internal variance as always large would itself distort by flattering fragmentation. The denominator therefore must be weighted by how operative a variant is, not by its mere existence in the record, and that weighting is contestable enough that a motivated comparer could tune it to reach either verdict. The control is real but it relocates the judgment rather than removing it.

